paragraphs.title: Init Spark - Load Data
paragraphs.text:
import org.apache.zeppelin.display.angular.paragraphscope._
import AngularElem._
import org.apache.spark.storage.StorageLevel
import scala.util.matching.Regex

// Define constants  
val tbl = "interesting"

val prefixes = Map( "^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#" -> "<rdf_",
                    "^<http://www.w3.org/2006/vcard/ns#" -> "<vcard_",
                    "^<http://schema.org/PostalAddress" -> "<schpa_",
                    "^<http://schema.org/" -> "<sch_",
                    "^<http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml/microdata#" -> "<md_",
                    "^<http://data-vocabulary.org/" -> "<dv_",
                    "^<http://purl.org/dc/terms/" -> "<dct_",
                    "^<http://rdf.data-vocabulary.org/#" -> "<rdv_",
                    "^<http://opengraphprotocol.org/schema/" -> "<ogps_",
                    "^<http://www.facebook.com/2008/" -> "<fb_",
                    "^<http://ogp.me/ns#" -> "<ogpm_")

def prefixIt(s:String) : String = {
    var res = s
    for ((k,v) <- prefixes)
        res = res.replaceFirst(k,v)
    
    return res.replaceFirst(">$","").replaceFirst("^<","").replaceAll("/","_")
}

// declare functin for sql engine 
sqlContext.udf.register("prefixIt", (s: String) => prefixIt(s))

// Load blacklist and whitelist of url 
spark.read.option("header","true").csv("whitelist.csv").createOrReplaceTempView("whitelist")
spark.read.option("header","true").csv("blacklist.csv").createOrReplaceTempView("blacklist")


val data = spark
    //.read.textFile("ofInterest.gz/*.txt")
    .sql("SELECT graph, subject, prefixIt(predicate) as predicate, object FROM "+tbl)
    //.read.parquet("open-data-plus/results/oneOfEach")
    .filter("graph IS NOT NULL")
    .filter("graph <> '' ")
    //.filter("graph NOT IN  (SELECT DISTINCT url FROM whitelist) ")
    //.filter("graph NOT IN  (SELECT DISTINCT url FROM blacklist) ")
    //.persist(StorageLevel.MEMORY_AND_DISK)
    
data.show
data.createOrReplaceTempView("data")

val dataContent = data.where("predicate <> 'rdf_type'  AND  predicate <> 'md_item'").cache
dataContent.createOrReplaceTempView("dataContent")

val dataTypes = data.where("""  
        predicate = 'rdf_type' 
    OR  predicate = 'md_item' """)
    .cache
dataTypes.createOrReplaceTempView("dataTypes")                        

val rdfType = dataTypes.filter("predicate = 'rdf_type'").cache
val microdata = dataTypes.filter("predicate = 'md_item'").cache

val leaf = dataContent.filter("object NOT LIKE '_:%'").cache
val bn = dataContent.filter("object LIKE '_:%'").cache

paragraphs.title: Basic structure
paragraphs.text:
%angular

RDF predicates

A first look at the data and some basic aggregate count later, we see what are the most popular predicate on webages.
  • rdf:type is the most common and that make sense! 15-25% estimate
  • vcard addresses seems more comon than schema.org addresses
  • Schema.org has many Address predicates
  • ... Take a look

Types of objects

Similarly, we can observe the rdf:type predicate and see what types of objects it describes the most. using filtering we can refine our search
  • The fields let you parameterize the query.
  • Fields are using SQL 'LIKE' syntax, please also keep the quotes
  • ...

paragraphs.title: Nantes
paragraphs.text:
%angular

Finding Nantes

We look for predicate that describes Nantes with as much uniqness as possible

Basic filtering

Applied to the whole data in a single read. We search for a few post code matching the city and the city name inside the NQuads. We filter the search on some very specific predicate.

Sibligns node

Here comes the issue, to find any form of neighbourhood we need to join the data to the original dataset. if its a small set then we can broadcast but here is the general method.

Parent / children

Capturing the parent node enable a second row much faster. Same for eventual children

Graph and Subject

A problem of the raw input is that it does not distinguish between subjet String, IRI, or blank node. Therefore, the join need to be done using both columns. We can here benefit from having sorting it by graph 4

Pivot on the predicate column

After we've grouped our data together, we begin to see patterns but also noise. more importantly, Entities remain as different rows and we would like to assemble them together. In order to find the address card we need to associate the predicates representing an address together. we use pivoting to do so since we already have already extracted the data

paragraphs.title: Code
paragraphs.text:
import spark.implicits._

var nantes = leaf.where("""
        (   
            predicate LIKE '%post%ode%'
            AND 
            object LIKE '%44%'
            )
        OR(
               (predicate LIKE '%ocality%'
                OR
                predicate LIKE '%address%'
                OR
                predicate LIKE '%title%')
            AND
            object LIKE '%Nantes%')
    """).as('nantes).dropDuplicates.cache
nantes.createOrReplaceTempView("nantes")
nantes.show
    
// TODO make the join take into account URL 
var hop1 = nantes.join(data.as('d), $"nantes.graph" === $"d.graph" && 
    ($"nantes.subject" === $"d.subject" || $"nantes.subject" === $"d.object" || $"nantes.object" === $"d.subject"))
                .select("d.graph","d.subject", "d.predicate", "d.object")
                .dropDuplicates
                .cache
            
//hop1.show
//hop1.createOrReplaceTempView("hop1")


var hop2 = hop1.as('hop1)
    .join(data.as('d2),  $"hop1.graph" === $"d2.graph"  &&
      ($"hop1.subject" === $"d2.subject" || $"hop1.subject" === $"d2.object" || $"hop1.object" === $"d2.subject"))
    .select("d2.graph","d2.subject", "d2.predicate", "d2.object")
    .dropDuplicates
    .cache
                
//hop2.show                
//hop2.createOrReplaceTempView("hop2")

var hop3 = hop2.as('hop2)
    .join(data.as('d),  $"hop2.graph" === $"d.graph"  &&
      ($"hop2.subject" === $"d.subject" || $"hop2.subject" === $"d.object" || $"hop2.object" === $"d.subject"))
    .select("d.graph","d.subject", "d.predicate", "d.object")
    .dropDuplicates
    .cache
                
//hop3.show                
//hop3.createOrReplaceTempView("hop3")
 
var siblings = nantes
    .join(data.as('d), $"nantes.graph" === $"d.graph" && $"nantes.subject" === $"d.subject")
    .select("d.graph","d.subject","d.predicate","d.object")

val bestpreds = siblings.groupBy("predicate").agg(count("*") as "cnt").orderBy(desc("cnt")).limit(20).cache
val arr = bestpreds.select("predicate").as[String].collect.toSeq
    
val addressCard= siblings.groupBy("graph","subject")
    .pivot("predicate", arr
    //Seq(
    //    "rdf_type",
    //    "vcard_locality", "vcard_postal-code", "vcard_street-address", "vcard_country-name", "vcard_adr", "vcard_region", "vcard_org",
    //    "sch_PostalAddress_addressLocality","sch_PostalAddress_addressCountry", "sch_PostalAddress_postalCode", 
    //    "sch_PostalAddress_streetAddress", "sch_Place_address", "sch_PostalAddress_addressRegion", "sch_LocalBusiness_address",
    //    "dv_Breadcrumb_url", "dv_Breadcrumb_title",
    //    "dct_title")
    )
    .agg(first("object"))
    .cache

addressCard.createOrReplaceTempView("addressCard")
addressCard.show()

paragraphs.title: Graph Expansion
paragraphs.text:
%spark.sql
SELECT hop2.predicate, cnt, cnt1, cnt2 FROM 
/* (SELECT count(*) as cnt3, predicate FROM hop3 GROUP BY predicate ) hop3
FULL JOIN */
 (SELECT count(*) as cnt2, predicate FROM hop2 GROUP BY predicate ) hop2
/*  ON hop3.predicate = hop2.predicate */
FULL JOIN
 (SELECT count(*) as cnt1, predicate FROM hop1 GROUP BY predicate ) hop1
  ON hop2.predicate = hop1.predicate 
FULL  JOIN
 (SELECT count(*) as cnt, predicate FROM nantes GROUP BY predicate ) n
  ON n.predicate =  hop2.predicate

ORDER BY cnt DESC, cnt1 DESC, cnt2 DESC

After we've grouped our data together, we begin to see patterns but also noise. more importantly, Entities remain as different rows and we would like to assemble them together.  

In order to find the address card we need to associate the predicates representing an address together. we use pivoting to do so since we already have already extracted the data

paragraphs.text:
import spark.implicits._

val preds = dataTypes.select(col("graph").as("g"),col("subject").as("s"),col("object").as("type"))
preds.select("type", "s").show(false)
    
val join = preds.join(dataContent, dataContent("graph") === preds("g") && dataContent("subject") === preds("s"), "right")
join.show

val schemas = join.select("type","predicate")
    .where("type LIKE '<%>' AND predicate LIKE '<%>' ")
    .groupBy("type","predicate")
    .pivot("type")
    .agg(count("predicate"));

schemas.show
schemas.write
    .mode("overwrite")
    .saveAsTable("schemas")
